<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 5 日星期六 01:40:28 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Wrong Way to Punish the FBI]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>消灭 FISA 第 702 条窃听将消除一个重要的反恐工具。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590088044158327442"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590088044158327442"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 6:39（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-fisa-section-702-surveillance-house-republicans-jim-jordan-christopher-wray-d13033e2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827128?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">联邦调查局局长克里斯托弗·雷</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布罗克斯坦/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>共和党人和所有美国人有充分的理由对联邦调查局的许多滥用职权感到愤怒。但当他们寻找如何制裁该局时，避免这样做的一种方法是杀死一名监视恐怖分子的有价值的情报机构。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这个错误在 7 月份的众议院司法委员会听证会上被列入议程，当时联邦调查局局长克里斯托弗·雷 (Christopher Wray) 就《外国情报监视法》(FISA) 中被称为第 702 条的部分内容接受质询。</p><p>弗吉尼亚州共和党人本·克莱恩表示，该计划“看起来像是一个框架，使联邦调查局能够监视无数美国人。”司法主席吉姆·乔丹表示，FBI 在其收集的外国监控数据中对美国人姓名进行了 204,000 次搜索，这是“共和党人反对以当前形式重新授权 FISA 的 204,000 个理由”。</p><p>有更好的理由保留它。国会在 9/11 事件后制定了第 702 条，以解决情报收集方面的缺陷。它允许政府在没有搜查令的情况下收集居住在国外的非美国公民的信息。这对于也门和巴基斯坦等地以及越来越重要的阿富汗很重要，基地组织和伊斯兰国在那里活动，但我们在当地不再有军队。</p><p>批评者称该计划针对的是美国人，但 702 的目的是收集涉及外国消息来源的通信。只有当美国人与外国情报目标有联系时，才能追踪国内消息来源，联邦调查局才能调查可疑通信。这对于识别可能接受国外指示的美国圣战分子至关重要。</p><p>共和党人和公民自由主义者指出，执法部门在数据中搜寻国内关键词，包括“黑人生命也是命”抗议者、1 月 6 日抗议者和共和党国会竞选活动的捐助者。这些都是严重的滥用行为，联邦调查局已采取措施解决这些问题。</p><p>雷先生告诉司法委员会，该机构“过去显然曾有过失败”，但改革已经在解决这些问题上发挥了很大作用。雷先生因拒绝坦诚回答其中一些虐待行为而受到怀疑。</p><p>但在 702 上，他得到了 5 月份 FISA 内部审计的支持，该审计显示数据库的不当使用已大大减少，使该机构的查询合规率为 96%，比改革前提高了 14%。</p><p>任何监视权力都有被滥用的风险。即使是需要法庭搜查令的窃听也是如此，正如我们从联邦调查局 (FBI) 在俄罗斯勾结惨败事件中向外国情报监视管理局 (FISA) 法庭撒的谎中了解到的那样，当时詹姆斯·科米 (James Comey)</p>管理局。<p></p><p>问题是滥用权力的风险是否值得预防恐怖袭击的好处。美国本土已经有一段时间没有遭受袭击了，但这并不意味着圣战分子和其他人如果可以的话就不会这样做。要求联邦调查局获得针对海外窃听的个人搜查令将导致延误，并阻止一些缺乏可能原因的搜查。取消联邦调查局的搜查权并迫使其依赖其他机构的推荐将降低该局的实时响应能力。</p><p>另一个可疑的想法是在 702 流程中注入一个外部监视器来唱反调。但如果存在滥用搜查，这就会削弱责任。国家安全是行政部门的责任，其官员滥用职权应受到制裁。科米联邦调查局的问题在于司法部的民主党人和白宫拒绝追究他的责任。</p><p>更好的想法是扩大对滥用 702 权限的特工的处罚，包括刑事处罚。出于政治原因向 FISA 法院撒谎并针对美国公民属于严重犯罪行为。</p><p>共和党人希望向联邦调查局传达一个信息，他们继续深入调查联邦调查局的失败和欺骗是正确的。雷先生非常令人失望。但如果共和党人拒绝重新授权第 702 条并且发生恐怖袭击，他们可能会仔细考虑政治后果。猜猜白宫和媒体会责怪谁，无论公平与否？</p><p>情报收集是民主国家相对于暗中活动的恐怖分子唯一的不对称优势之一。凶手只需逃避侦查一次即可谋杀无辜者。废除 702 条款可能会给美国人带来比 FBI 更大的惩罚。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=26E47143-A26A-4B2E-8493-301BBB0F63D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffbi-fisa-section-702-surveillance-house-republicans-jim-jordan-christopher-wray-d13033e2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：在德文·阿彻向众议院监督委员会作证期间，出现了一幅亨特·拜登在布里斯马董事会的角色如何与副总统乔·拜登的乌克兰外交混在一起的画面。图片：EFE via ZUMA Press/Reuters 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 22:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-fisa-section-702-surveillance-house-republicans-jim-jordan-christopher-wray-d13033e2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fbi-fisa-section-702-surveillance-house-republicans-jim-jordan-christopher-wray-d13033e2<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>隐私问题/信息安全</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>窃听/电子窃听</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>外国情报安全局</category><category>联邦调查局</category><category>克里斯托弗·雷</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>隐私问题</category><category>信息安全</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>窃听</category><category>电子窃听</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Democrats Want a Trump O.J. Simpson Trial]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>亚当·希夫希望法庭上有电视摄像机。他为什么想要那个？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590130633942813058"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590130633942813058"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 6:28 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-trial-cameras-courtroom-roslynn-mauskopf-adam-schiff-democrats-b24375e2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830376?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">众议员亚当·希夫 (Adam Schiff) 7 月 13 日在华盛顿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布罗克斯坦/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>我们一直在告诉您，民主党人希望<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>的审判在 2024 年 11 月的选举中占据媒体的注意力，但请不要相信我们的话。以亚当·希夫的为例。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周四，这位即将竞选 2024 年参议员的加州众议员和特朗普的主要对手，带领大约三打民主党人游说司法会议，向电视镜头开放对特朗普先生的联邦审判。</p><p>议员们写信给联邦法院行政办公室司法会议秘书罗斯林·莫斯科普夫法官，“鉴于这些案件中提出的指控的历史性，很难想象还有比电视直播诉讼更有力的情况了。” “如果公众要完全接受结果，那么尽可能直接地见证审判的进行方式、证据的强度以及证人的可信度至关重要。”</p><p>特朗普可能因最新指控受审的联邦地方法院不允许摄像头。合理的原因是相机可能会分散人们寻求公平正义的过程。这是特朗普审判中的一个特殊风险，无论如何，这将是一场全球媒体的马戏表演。</p><p>但这正是民主党想要的：一场旷日持久的 OJ 辛普森式审判，吸引公众和政界的关注，特别是如果它在 2024 年选举日之前进行的话。</p><p>鉴于美国的政治两极分化和这次起诉的性质，民主党声称电视摄像机将使公众更有可能接受判决的可能性极小。现任总统的司法部正在起诉他的潜在对手。那本质上是可燃的。</p><p>唐纳德·特朗普的审判如果没有各个参与者在镜头前播放并观看晚间有线电视新闻的评论，那将是足够痛苦的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=526AA661-97D0-46C2-9AB6-B4C8E9331062&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-trial-cameras-courtroom-roslynn-mauskopf-adam-schiff-democrats-b24375e2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：特别检察官杰克·史密斯的最新起诉书基于针对美国的广泛且新颖的欺诈理论，并服务于民主党的目标，即在 2021 年 1 月 6 日举行公投。图片来源：Jane Rosenberg/Reuters/AP综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 22:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-trial-cameras-courtroom-roslynn-mauskopf-adam-schiff-democrats-b24375e2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-trial-cameras-courtroom-roslynn-mauskopf-adam-schiff-democrats-b24375e2<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亚当·希夫</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Calling Josh Shapiro’s Voucher Bluff]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>一位工会领袖和一位民主党人为宾夕法尼亚州的择校法案带来了新的希望。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130171244533514"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130171244533514"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 6:27 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amen-brown-ryan-boyer-pennsylvania-vouchers-josh-shapiro-philadelphia-school-choice-6cdf9bd0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830372?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">宾夕法尼亚州州长乔什·夏皮罗</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·洛克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周四，宾夕法尼亚州州长乔什·夏皮罗否决了他在屈服于工会和民主党控制的众议院之前支持的 1 亿美元代金券提案，令数千名家长感到失望。但两名反对奖学金的人士表明，如果共和党利用其立法影响力，奖学金并不会消失。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>费城民主党众议员阿门·布朗本周强化了他对择校的支持。他在广播节目中说：“我们必须给父母另一种选择，让他们自己选择希望孩子去哪里。” “我们向系统中投入了多少，却没有任何改变？”</p><p>碰巧的是，费城为每个学生花费超过 21,000 美元用于失败工厂，这些工厂中大多数学生无法达到其年级水平的阅读能力。 2021-22 学年，费城 34% 的学生精通英语语言艺术，数学精通的比例高达 15%。怎么会有人捍卫这样的结果呢？</p><p>布朗发表此番言论之前，费城建筑行业委员会主席瑞安·博耶（Ryan Boyer）在《费城公民》杂志上<a href="https://thephiladelphiacitizen.org/guest-commentary-i-95-school-choice/" target="_blank" class="icon none">撰文称</a>，他“对任何能够帮助家庭更好地教育孩子、让他们做好成为社会富有成效的成员的解决方案持开放态度。” ”博耶表示，他送儿子去私立学校读书，“反对择校就是伪君子”。</p><p>尽管夏皮罗州长本周签署了一份没有凭证的预算法案，但预算过程尚未结束。共和党控制的参议院必须起草并通过财政法规立法，以实施许多预算项目，包括几个民主党的优先事项。共和党人可以利用这一机会，通过将奖学金与众议院的愿望清单挂钩来恢复奖学金。</p><p> “我们真的会因为 1 亿美元而让整个州暂停，还是会说，你知道吗，好吧，让我们退后一步，真正权衡一下选择？”布朗众议员说。</p><p>州长的否决信息留下了一些回旋余地，让他从去年竞选时向工会屈辱的投降中恢复过来：“改善和扩大儿童的机会仍然是我的首要任务，我认为这是各方未竟的事业我们必须共同努力前进。”</p><p>夏皮罗先生的重新推动将为其他费城民主党人提供政治掩护，他们可能愿意支持代金券，但会受到工会反对的恐吓。共和党人，继续施加压力。你们拥有道德、教育和政治制高点。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=954997AE-F15A-4DBE-8FC9-6D52B724218A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famen-brown-ryan-boyer-pennsylvania-vouchers-josh-shapiro-philadelphia-school-choice-6cdf9bd0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：查尔斯·佩恩采访佐治亚州众议员梅沙·梅诺。图片：美联社/福克斯新闻 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 22:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amen-brown-ryan-boyer-pennsylvania-vouchers-josh-shapiro-philadelphia-school-choice-6cdf9bd0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/amen-brown-ryan-boyer-pennsylvania-vouchers-josh-shapiro-philadelphia-school-choice-6cdf9bd0<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>共和党</category><category>费城民主党</category><category>阿门·布朗</category><category>乔什·夏皮罗</category><category>瑞恩·博耶</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>教育</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Rare Justice Department Mea Culpa]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>检察官承认他们对毕马威欺诈案的起诉是错误的。显然奇迹会发生。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128791701489962"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128791701489962"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 6:27 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/justice-department-pcaob-kpmg-fraud-david-middendorf-jeffrey-wada-c27e6cb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830374?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">位于洛杉矶市中心的毕马威会计师事务所大楼。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：萨姆·米尔科维奇/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>检察官很少承认错误。因此，本周，纽约南区美国检察官办公室承认错误地起诉了前毕马威审计师和会计监管机构，这几乎是奇迹。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>这些起诉是过去十年备受瞩目的“偷考”丑闻的一部分，该丑闻涉及毕马威会计师事务所及其在上市公司会计监督委员会（PCAOB）的监督人员。在检查中获得低分后，毕马威审计师试图从 PCAOB 员工那里获取有关审计将被检查的预先信息。</p><p>一名 PCAOB 检查负责人、前机构雇员后来离职前往毕马威 (KPMG) 工作，向审计师泄露了有关检查选择的信息。毕马威审计人员利用这些技巧来改进他们的审计。简而言之，审计师在监管机构的怂恿下在检查考试中作弊。这是不诚实的行为，但这是否构成犯罪？</p><p>司法部表示确实如此，并于 2018 年指控前毕马威合伙人戴维·米登多夫 (David Middendorf) 和前 PCAOB 员工杰弗里·瓦达 (Jeffrey Wada) 合谋进行电汇欺诈并诈骗美国，另外四人认罪。 2019 年，米登多夫和世界反兴奋剂机构因电汇欺诈指控被定罪。</p><p>此后，联邦法院驳回了政府用来起诉这两人的广泛欺诈理论。 2020 年，最高法院一致推翻了对前新泽西州州长克里斯·克里斯蒂 (Chris Christie) 助手的欺诈定罪（<em>凯利诉美国案）</em> ，这些助手涉嫌密谋造成乔治华盛顿大桥交通堵塞，以作为政治报复。</p><p>法官们认为，共谋实施电汇欺诈必须涉及剥夺某人金钱或实际财产的计划。 “陪审团听到的证据无疑表明存在不当行为——欺骗、腐败、滥用权力，”法官埃琳娜·卡根(Elena Kagan)为法院写道。 “但有争议的联邦欺诈法规并未将所有此类行为定为犯罪。”</p><p>去年 12 月，第二巡回上诉法院驳回了对获得机密医疗保险报销信息的交易员和顾问的欺诈定罪。今年五月，第一巡回法院驳回了因大学蓝调大学招生丑闻而被指控的富裕父母的欺诈定罪，因为招生名额不是“财产”。</p><p>正如曼哈顿美国检察官办公室本周在要求第二巡回法院取消对米登多夫和和反机构的定罪时所承认的那样，PCAOB 的检查名单也不是这样。这些指控本不应该提出，但检察官常常无法抗拒诱惑，将刑法延伸到监狱中，以监禁他们认为令人反感的人。</p><p>正如高等法院一直强调的那样，并非所有不诚实行为都是联邦犯罪。今年五月，法官们一致驳回了两项过于宽泛的欺诈理论，推翻了前州长安德鲁·科莫亲信的定罪。克拉伦斯·托马斯法官</p>在一份意见中指出，政府的理论“极大地将联邦管辖范围扩大到几乎无限种的欺骗行为。”<p></p><p>这是杰克·史密斯对唐纳德·特朗普串谋诈骗美国的最新指控的一个问题。法院具有里程碑意义的<em>斯基林</em>（2010）判决极大地限制了模糊的诚实服务欺诈法规下的起诉。但检察官不断发明新理论，将不诚实行为定为刑事犯罪，并在上诉中不断败诉。</p><p>美国检察官在毕马威案件中的认错值得欢迎，但如果检察官没有等待数年才坦白就更好了。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D92112D3-1820-448C-AE31-7108C18E7810&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fjustice-department-pcaob-kpmg-fraud-david-middendorf-jeffrey-wada-c27e6cb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：现在困扰唐纳德·特朗普和亨特·拜登的法律问题的核心是“没有人可以凌驾于法律之上”。瓦格纳集团的叶夫根尼·普里戈任提供了另一种选择：没有规则。图片：美联社/法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 22:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/justice-department-pcaob-kpmg-fraud-david-middendorf-jeffrey-wada-c27e6cb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/justice-department-pcaob-kpmg-fraud-david-middendorf-jeffrey-wada-c27e6cb<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>会计</category><category>会计/咨询</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>监管机构</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>上市公司会计监督委员会</category><category>毕马威会计师事务所</category><category>杰弗里·瓦达</category><category>大卫·米登多夫</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>监管机构</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>会计</category><category>咨询</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Chris Christie Prosecutes the Political Case Against Trump]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>前新泽西州州长表示，前总统“无法赢得”2024 年大选。 “他可能会在四个不同的司法管辖区获得保释。” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124511850921480"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590124511850921480"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kyle-peterson" itemprop="url" rel="author">凯尔·彼得森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 5:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecuting-the-political-case-against-trump-indictment-hunter-biden-president-campign-2024-debate-40d77b38"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829953?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">插图：芭芭拉·凯利</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>克里斯·克里斯蒂有一个关于如何击败唐纳德·特朗普的理论：攻击他。如果这听起来像是“傻瓜选举”中的内容，那么它在 2024 年共和党竞选中基本上还没有经过考验，根据周五 RealClearPolitics 的平均值，特朗普以 53% 的支持率领先。 “这场比赛中没有其他人愿意与他较量，”克里斯蒂先生说。 “他们要么都在争取在潜在的特朗普内阁中占据一席之地，要么就是没有能力做到这一点。除非你打败他，否则你就没有办法打败他。”</p><p>在周二访问《华尔街日报》时，这位两任新泽西州州长对特朗普毫不留情。 “他是总统任期内最大的骗子，这是一个需要清除的很高的门槛，但他已经清除了，”克里斯蒂先生说。无论今天的民调结果如何，他都坚信特朗普肯定会输给拜登总统。 “特朗普赢不了，”他说。 “当我们三周后进入辩论阶段时，他可能会在四个不同的司法管辖区获得保释。”</p><p>克里斯蒂先生的麻烦在于，即使他对大选的看法是正确的，在那之前也可能并不重要。总体而言，特朗普受到共和党人的喜爱，而被起诉似乎提高了他的地位。到 2024 年 11 月，独立人士和郊区妈妈们发表意见时，克里斯蒂先生可能会和我们其他人一起坐在沙发上观看。他只有几个月的时间让共和党相信，特朗普在从竞选站点飞往法庭时不可能获胜。</p><p> “我做了这项工作七年，”克里斯蒂先生说。 “我知道他面临的是什么。”这是指他以前担任新泽西州联邦检察官的工作，该州是约 900 万人的最高联邦检察官。在写完自己的起诉书后，他毫不犹豫地驳斥了针对特朗普的第一组指控。曼哈顿地区检察官阿尔文·布拉格 (Alvin Bragg) 在 4 月提出指控，指控这位前总统在 2016 年付钱给斯托米·丹尼尔斯 (Stormy Daniels)，让他对他们涉嫌的婚外情保持沉默后，伪造了商业记录。</p><p> “纽约就是一个笑话，”克里斯蒂先生说。 “他们正在将这些法规延伸到绝对极限，我认为超出了这些极限，”布拉格先生任由城市生活恶化，对一个长达七年的封口费案件的定罪“不会改善城市的生活质量”。曼哈顿岛一闪而过。”</p><p>第二份起诉书则有所不同。特别检察官杰克·史密斯 (Jack Smith) 于 6 月获得了这份报告，指控特朗普不当处理机密文件并加以掩盖。克里斯蒂称这是“一起严重的案件，有确凿的证据”，如果得到证实，“绝对违法”。正如克里斯蒂先生所说，在特朗普收到海湖庄园安全录像传票后不久，他援引《教父》的说法，派“弗雷多”删除服务器：“这是典型的妨碍司法公正的行为。”</p><p>克里斯蒂继续说道，联邦政府“悄悄地、专业地、私下要求他在 18 个月内归还文件”。 “当然，他没有，因为他太忙了。”讽刺是面无表情的。 “我观察了他这 18 个月的所作所为。似乎每天都在打高尔夫球，”他说。 “我认为他可以挤出几分钟的时间。”相反，特朗普“派弗雷多和另一个人跑来跑去搬箱子，不让他自己的律师看到它们，然后允许他的律师提交一份证明，表明他们已经审查了所有内容。”</p><p>共和党人之所以支持特朗普，部分原因是他们看到了克里斯蒂认可的双重标准。他说，如果希拉里·克林顿因她的地下室电子邮件服务器而被指控，“我们就不会进行这次对话”，而奥巴马政府放走她，“绝对是在玩政治”。但他并不认为答案是给下一个共和党藐视者一张“免出狱”卡。 “我们一直把检察官视为问题所在，”他说，“而不是唐纳德·特朗普。他做了这些事。”</p><p>至于亨特·拜登，</p>克里斯蒂先生在与联邦法官接触后就税务和枪支犯罪问题达成了认罪协议，他表示如果一名检察官给他带来了“单方面”的协议，他就会解雇他。 “这要么是双重标准，要么是完全无能的证据，对于特拉华州美国检察官办公室来说，我认为至少有 30% 的可能性是完全无能，”他说。 “这是一间简陋的办公室。”他估计该州雇用的检察官数量是他在新泽西州监督的检察官的八分之一。克里斯蒂认为，此事需要一位特别检察官的管辖权，“还要审查目前针对总统参与其儿子生意的指控”。<p></p><p>这就剩下第三项起诉书，指控特朗普密谋推翻 2020 年大选。克里斯蒂离开大楼数小时后发布了该消息。他在推特上写道，特朗普“违反了他的誓言，给他的总统任期带来了耻辱”。一位发言人告诉我们，他的日程安排不允许他详细说明。原来他正在前往乌克兰基辅的途中。</p><p>当克里斯蒂认为这些指控有理有据时，他的态度就是忽视政治影响，让正义得到伸张。他说：“如果事实证明起诉唐纳德·特朗普再次当选总统，虽然这会让我深感困扰，但更令我困扰的是，如果我们让他对国家犯下的重大罪行却逍遥法外。” “这就是他所指望的，除了他巨大的自我之外，这是他竞选的唯一原因。你认为他对这个国家不屑一顾，而他却为国家的未来制定了所有这些伟大的计划？你听过他们中的任何一个吗？</p><p>那么，克里斯蒂先生对国家的未来有什么伟大的计划吗？他说：“首先，我们必须重新控制政府支出。”他声称自己在新泽西州就是这么做的。 “我在 290 亿美元的预算中继承了 110 亿美元的赤字，每个人都说我必须提高税收来平衡赤字。我没有。我们已经八年没有加税了，第一年，我们从预算中削减了 836 个单独项目。”</p><p>克里斯蒂先生希望为 K-12 学校提供通用优惠券。 “在纽瓦克市，我们为每个学生花费 36,000 美元。在阿斯伯里帕克，我们为每个学生花费了 40,000 美元，但效果却非常糟糕，”他说。 “为什么不把这笔钱分给每个家庭，放在一个受控账户里，让他们可以用于教育，把孩子送到他们想去的地方？”学校教育是州和地方的一项职能，但克里斯蒂先生表示，总统可以利用权力讲坛并对联邦资金设置条件。</p><p> “在犯罪方面，我厌倦了纽约、芝加哥、洛杉矶、旧金山以及所有这些地方正在发生的事情，”他说。 “我将前往每一个州并任命美国检察官，他们向我发出的政策指示是追查每一个城市的暴力犯罪，取代地方当局，将这些人纳入联邦，并将他们关进监狱。当当地厌倦了我们的干预时，他们就会回去自己做。”</p><p>他称自己是“乌克兰毫不掩饰的支持者”，并表示，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京(Vladimir Putin)</a>去年入侵之前，他早就向乌克兰的捍卫者派遣了大枪。 “我认为拜登的政策失败了，因为他们给的钱刚好够他们赢不了，”他说。 “特朗普对阻止战争不感兴趣。他有兴趣继续与普京成为朋友。所以他所做的只是足以比奥巴马做的更多。”</p><p>克里斯蒂还认为，来自蓝州的共和党州长习惯于与民主党立法机构讨价还价，可能会改变两极分化的华盛顿的动态，因为华盛顿已经忘记了如何完成任何事情。 “这需要与国会议员发展关系——这真的很糟糕，”他说。 “我会和我无法忍受的人一起吃更多的晚餐、午餐、饮料和活动。”作为州长，他的电话有时会在晚上 11:30 响起，“通常几乎都是参议院议长打来的，”他回忆道。 “我总是接电话。”</p><p>为什么他针对特朗普先生的案件没有得到更多关注？ “我不知道，”他说。 “八个星期是我提出这个论点的时间。但请再给我一点时间。”他有资源坚持下去直到投票吗？ “嗯，当我们今天坐在这里时，我当然没有它们，”他承认。 “听着，如果我在辩论台上表演，我会筹集更多的钱，如果我不表演，我就不会。”就连克里斯蒂先生似乎也知道自己在冒险，尽管最近新罕布什尔州的一项民意调查显示他的支持率为 11%，位居第三，落后于佛罗里达州州长罗恩·德桑蒂斯 ( <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> )（13%）。</p><p>一个缺点是60岁的克里斯蒂先生不再是一个新鲜面孔。他已经离开办公室五年了，一直在进行游说并占据电视节目的时间。他永远无法超越“桥门”的呼声，尽管他坚称李堡的一些交通问题不是他下令的。 2016 年总统初选失利后，他成为第一个支持特朗普的共和党大人物，并差点被任命为副总统。然后他没有获得司法部长的职位。他拒绝了较少的内阁职位，这很公平：没有孩子梦想长大后成为劳工部长。</p><p>克里斯蒂先生希望这段历史能让他的批评可信，前提是共和党人愿意记住他从来都不是一个“永不特朗普”的人。 “我实际上是从这样的角度出发的，我试图让这个人成为更好的候选人，”他说。 “我试图让他成为一名更好的总统。”他从 2016 年初选中吸取的教训是，特朗普的对手不能坐等地心引力将他拉倒。</p><p>这一次，克里斯蒂的计划是把火力瞄准特朗普。或者，至少是他的大部分火力。 2024 年的困境与上次没什么不同，那就是，如果共和党人想迅速将竞争范围缩小到特朗普先生和一个挑战者，克里斯蒂先生和其他人知道他们需要成为顶端的螃蟹发生时桶的。尽管他对特朗普先生很愤怒，但他对德桑蒂斯先生也很严厉。</p><p> “如果我们认可简历，那么德桑蒂斯的竞选活动即使不是领先，也会与特朗普并驾齐驱。我们不这样做，”克里斯蒂先生说。 “你实际上必须走出去，成为一个人——成为一个人，并表明你可以与其他人建立联系，你希望获得他们的选票。”他得到了一些笑声。两天前，德桑蒂斯先生在新罕布什尔州拉伊市的一次烧烤会上讲述了这一点，似乎是为了说明这一点。 5,600：“所有这些深层势力的人，你知道，我们从第一天起就会开始割喉。”</p><p>随后克里斯蒂先生对德桑蒂斯先生大加赞赏。 “你想死在的那座山上是佛罗里达州K-12学区的非裔美国人研究课程吗？好的。您想发送同性恋视频，然后假装它们不是您的，但随后被发现，它们是您的？我的意思是，这就像业余时间。人们看到这一点后，他们会想，哦，<em>也许</em>他还没有准备好当总统。”</p><p>德桑蒂斯的支持者强调了他在佛罗里达州的记录。克里斯蒂先生认为这是“一个红色州，拥有红色立法机构，没有明显的批评媒体”，并暗示杰布·布什在 2016 年因类似原因被高估了。他说，放弃这些佛罗里达州政客吧。 “他们没有打架。如果你是共和党人，那就像下面的糖果乐园。只是——我的意思是，来吧。我一生中从未见过比这更顺从的立法机构。”</p><p>如果用路易斯维尔重击手追击德桑蒂斯对于承诺关注特朗普的候选人来说似乎是一种奇怪的策略，那么这可能是政治动机。或者也许艺人克里斯蒂先生根本无法抗拒好材料。 8 月 23 日的辩论也可能证明同样的情况。 “我不打算带着猎枪走上舞台，然后开始向整个地方喷洒铅弹，”他说。 “现在，如果有人说了一些极其愚蠢的话，而我认为现在是时候说，‘这真的很愚蠢’，我就会这么做。”</p><p><em>彼得森先生是该杂志编辑委员会的成员。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=526AA661-97D0-46C2-9AB6-B4C8E9331062&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fprosecuting-the-political-case-against-trump-indictment-hunter-biden-president-campign-2024-debate-40d77b38&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：特别检察官杰克·史密斯的最新起诉书基于针对美国的广泛且新颖的欺诈理论，并服务于民主党的目标，即在 2021 年 1 月 6 日举行公投。图片来源：Jane Rosenberg/Reuters/AP综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecuting-the-political-case-against-trump-indictment-hunter-biden-president-campign-2024-debate-40d77b38</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/prosecuting-the-political-case-against-trump-indictment-hunter-biden-president-campign-2024-debate-40d77b38<author><![CDATA[Kyle Peterson]]></author><category>选举</category><category>总统</category><category>2024年</category><category>共和党</category><category>选民</category><category>起诉书</category><category>辩论</category><category>新泽西州</category><category>活动</category><category>政府开支</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>优惠券</category><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>采访</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>采访</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Curtains for Hollywood, Pages for Me]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>演员和编剧的罢工可能会给我提供创作所需的推动力。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098080331102618"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590098080331102618"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">丹尼·海特曼</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 5:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/curtains-for-hollywood-pages-for-me-tv-books-reading-bucket-list-e5221527"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825149?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>好莱坞作家和演员正在罢工，我在家庭电视上方几英寸处制定了应急计划。比控制台稍高的长架子上有两打我从未抽出时间阅读的经典著作。没有新的电视节目和电影，我将有足够的时间来赶上。</p><p>当我们进入夏季的最后冲刺阶段时，这个想法就浮现在脑海中，这个季节的特点是在摇曳的吊床上度过漫长的下午，当我们在散文的轻柔波浪中摇摆时，厚厚的书籍将我们固定在原地。这是一个可爱的理想，尽管我经常发现它难以捉摸，因为本月我在随身携带贝丽尔·马卡姆（Beryl Markham）的复古版《夜色西下》时有人提醒我。我买了一本马卡姆 1942 年著名回忆录的平装本，讲述了她在非洲当飞行员的岁月，当时新版本于 1983 年首次出版。四十年后，我终于揭开了封面，每周阅读一章。按照这样的速度，我每天都会在花园杂务和避暑别墅的客人中挤出一两页。我可能会在秋天的树叶开始转动时结束。与此同时，我的阅读积压也在增加。</p><p>我从来没有在夏天或任何其他季节读书，尽管我认为我会读书。我怀疑我并不孤单。即使在 Covid-19 封锁期间（有报道称，与世隔绝的美国人急切地研读普鲁斯特和托尔斯泰的著作），我也没有获得我所希望的阅读财富。我刚刚开始一份新工作，这把我的精力转移到了其他地方。我的那本《战争与和平》仍然完好无损。</p><p>即便如此，读者仍然生活在希望之中。也许好莱坞电影的匮乏会促使我把伊芙琳·沃 (Evelyn Waugh) 1938 年的漫画小说《独家新闻》(Scoop) 从我的愿望清单上划掉。如果运气好的话，威廉·麦克斯韦的大量短篇小说集和陀思妥耶夫斯基的《罪与罚》也可以从我的待读书架上移走。</p><p>作为一名电视观众，我可能会发起一场小小的罢工。</p><p><em>海特曼先生是《巴吞鲁日倡导者》的专栏作家，也是 Phi Kappa Phi 的《论坛》杂志的编辑。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1E96F6DF-1AFD-492E-88F0-B9583D3F172F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcurtains-for-hollywood-pages-for-me-tv-books-reading-bucket-list-e5221527&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">随着流媒体扰乱电视和电影行业的经济，它不会像迪士尼通过重塑经典童话故事（包括即将上映的《白雪公主》）那样以政治姿态疏远观众。图片来源：Disney/Shutterstock/Bloomberg News/Getty Images for CAA Composite：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/curtains-for-hollywood-pages-for-me-tv-books-reading-bucket-list-e5221527</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/curtains-for-hollywood-pages-for-me-tv-books-reading-bucket-list-e5221527<category>电视</category><category>图书</category><category>阅读</category><category>好书</category><category>好莱坞</category><category>罢工</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Eternal Truths Cast in Bronze: Rodin’s ‘The Gates of Hell’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>奥古斯特·罗丹未完成的项目是他作为现代雕塑之父和引人注目的人性肖像的遗产的基石。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827733" alt="奥古斯特·罗丹，《地狱之门》（演员 1926-28）" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>奥古斯特·罗丹，《地狱之门》（1926-28 年演员） 费城艺术博物馆<span>费城艺术博物馆</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126303181863836"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590126303181863836"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">朱莉娅·费舍尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日下午 5:45 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>在奥古斯特·罗丹（Auguste Rodin，1840-1917）的整个职业生涯中，他都直视失败。罗丹出生于一个贫穷的家庭，他曾三次申请进入巴黎美术学院——当时法国有抱负的艺术家的重要踏脚石——但一次又一次被拒绝。所以他必须自己走自己的路。他的雕塑经常遭到嘲笑和拒绝。直到三十多岁时，这位巴黎人的作品才引发了真正的兴趣——无论是积极的还是消极的。他的突破性雕塑《青铜时代》（1875）是一尊全尺寸的站立男性裸体，栩栩如生，以至于批评者指责罗丹直接从模型中制作模型。</p><p> 《地狱之门》被广泛认为是罗丹最伟大的作品，但也可能被认为是失败的。 1880 年，罗丹收到委托，为巴黎一座新的装饰艺术博物馆制作两扇带有浮雕的门，展示但丁的《神曲》。博物馆从未建成，但罗丹一直在创作《大门》，直到他去世——他生命的一半——此时它们仍未完成。最初的石膏模型现藏于奥赛博物馆，但 1917 年之后又制作了多个青铜铸件，可在世界各地的博物馆中看到。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">&#39;The Gates of Hell&#39; (1880-1917) by Auguste Rodin</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Eternal Truths Cast in Bronze </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829113/"> &#39;The Three Shades&#39; at the top of &#39;The Gates of Hell,&#39; Auguste Rodin <span class="imageCredit">Philadelphia Museum of Art</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829114/"> &#39;The Thinker&#39; on &#39;The Gates of Hell,&#39; Auguste Rodin <span class="imageCredit">Philadelphia Museum of Art</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829118/"> Another view of &#39;The Thinker&#39; on &#39;The Gates of Hell,&#39; Auguste Rodin <span class="imageCredit">Philadelphia Museum of Art</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829115/"> &#39;The Falling Man,&#39; one of several casts on &#39;The Gates of Hell,&#39; Auguste Rodin <span class="imageCredit">Philadelphia Museum of Art</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-829117/"> &#39;Paolo and Francesca&#39; on &#39;The Gates of Hell,&#39; Auguste Rodin <span class="imageCredit">Philadelphia Museum of Art</span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p> From afar, the doors are a grand, rectangular shape, 20 feet tall and 13 feet wide, with intricate forms twisting like vines in the margins of an illuminated manuscript.近距离观察，它们几乎是可怕的。整个作品中充斥着人体的刺耳声音。虽然出现了大约 180 个人形，但在某一时刻出现的人数超过 200 人。罗丹以洛伦佐·吉贝尔蒂的《天堂之门》（1425-52）、佛罗伦萨洗礼堂的青铜门和米开朗基罗的《最后的审判》（1535-41）为模型。但在对受诅咒者扭曲身体的流畅、无等级的描绘中，罗丹创造了自己的东西。金属框架内的形态的动态运动永无止境。事实上，它们似乎并未受到遏制。灵魂向观众伸出援手，超越了门的界限。例如，在左上角，一个男性人物——“坠落的人”——像攀岩者一样倒挂着，他肌肉发达的手臂抓住了门楣。 Below him lies a chaotic whirlwind from which he seems determined to escape.</p><p> And though Rodin eventually abandoned a direct representation of Dante&#39;s poem, the sculpture still shows the poet&#39;s influence.罗丹最著名的作品“思想者”上方浮现出面孔和头骨。 Originally intended to represent Dante himself, the figure later shed specificity, instead symbolizing contemplation.</p><p> Of all the people in the doors, “The Thinker” might be the most static in his pose, but even this piece of “The Gates” demonstrates Rodin&#39;s genius.正如雕塑家所言：“我的思想者之所以思考，是因为他不仅用他的大脑、他皱起的眉头、他扩张的鼻孔和紧缩的嘴唇来思考，而且还用他手臂、背部和腿部的每一块肌肉，以及他紧握的拳头和嘴唇来思考。夹住脚趾。”这种身体特征在所有人物中都有体现。罗丹对人体解剖学的表现力处理几乎让人想起戈雅的画作。他不是简单地复制一种形式，而是捕捉身体背后发自内心的、完整的感觉力量。这既定义了“大门”，也解释了它们的重要性。自文艺复兴以来，艺术一直是一种讲故事的媒介。 But here, Rodin abandons the traditional narrative and makes the human form a “story” of its own, using pose and gesture alone to express ideas and emotions—in this case, man&#39;s tragic fate.</p><p> And so, as in Dante&#39;s hell, the damned interact with one another, both helping and harming.一男一女，但丁笔下的保罗和弗朗西斯卡，紧紧地抱在一起，不顾一切地想要保持彼此陪伴的舒适感。 （“吻”最初是门的一部分，也是受到悲剧恋人的启发。）在“思想者”的右边，惊慌失措的灵魂践踏和推挤。这位雕塑家在他那个时代受到严厉批评的原因是显而易见的：他的作品毫不畏惧地大胆、感性和风格化。 For an eternity in which bodies are left behind, Rodin&#39;s hell is startlingly material.</p><p> The way that Rodin composed the “The Gates” broke with artistic convention as well.他在一些地方回收人物。 The “Three Shades” at the top, for example, are casts of the same sculpture, anticipating Picasso&#39;s invention of assemblage—making sculpture out of pre-existing materials.</p><p> Rodin had a devout Catholic upbringing, and briefly joined a religious order after his beloved sister died.然而，除了对但丁甚至基督教地狱世界的精彩描绘之外，《大门》对人类苦难进行了惊人的呈现。通过他的艺术反叛，罗丹将他捕捉到的悲剧普遍化。门口住的不是拿着干草叉的恶魔，而是人类，他们的未实现的渴望给他们带来了永恒的痛苦。 《地狱之门》创作于 19 世纪和 20 世纪之交，借鉴了文艺复兴时期的资料，但在今天仍然雄辩地向我们讲述着。 Admiring them on a fresh autumn day at Philadelphia&#39;s Rodin Museum, as I did nearly two years ago, one must still reckon with an internal hell.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Fischer is a Robert L. Bartley</p> Fellow at the Journal.<p></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:45:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/eternal-truths-cast-in-bronze-rodins-the-gates-of-hell-5ea6f0bb<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[It’s DOJ vs. DOJ in the 2024 Election]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> What will voters take to the polls? Its collusion-hoax findings, or the accusations against Trump? <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130033451633158"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590130033451633158"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Holman W. Jenkins</span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name">Jr.</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 5:38 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829980?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Justice Department seal in Washington, Nov. 28, 2018.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jose Luis Magana/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The odds are not small that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> could be the next president of the United States. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> has made it clear to all concerned he wants Mr. Trump to be his GOP opponent.到目前为止，这些指控只会让特朗普更加坚定。显然，他们让任何共和党人都很难有效地挑战他。</p><p> You&#39;re a career employee in Joe Biden&#39;s Justice Department, serving as US attorney for his home state, a job you wouldn&#39;t have if not sponsored by the state&#39;s two Democratic senators, both lifelong Joe allies.你要把这本书扔给他的儿子亨特吗？当然不是。答案不可能是别的。 After all, more worrisome to the public even than evidence of favoritism would be an inkling that Mr. Biden&#39;s DOJ was going out of its way to undermine its own president.</p><p> You&#39;re in the unique position of a Justice Department special counsel, given unlimited resources to investigate a single person, the president&#39;s political enemy, Donald Trump. Do you play it conservatively despite knowing that any indictment today would be more politically useful to your president than a conviction after the election?</p><p> The unsolvability paradox is redolent in the department&#39;s own policy of not taking investigative acts before an election.当然，不采取通常采取的行动也是影响选举的一种方式。</p><p> It&#39;s an impossible situation. The only hope would be an attorney general of such soaring, Lincolnesque stature that his conflicted, inevitably politicized decisions compel unquestioning buy-in</p><p> This does not describe Merrick Garland, estimable though he may be.因此，今天的传球确实很糟糕。 The 2024 election will be arbitrated by a debate about how corrupt the Justice Department is or isn&#39;t.</p><p> Two antecedents strike me as important.比以往任何时候都更加清楚的是，奥巴马政府应该立即解雇联邦调查局局长詹姆斯·科米，因为他在希拉里·克林顿电子邮件案中做出了不当、违反协议的行为。他的行为嘲笑了奥巴马政府部门在是否起诉克林顿这一令人烦恼的决定中理应承担的政治责任。 Allowed to carry on, Mr. Comey committed the further improper acts that put Mr. Trump in the White House and fanned the collusion farce.</p><p> The worst institutional failure, though, is the press&#39;s handling of the collusion hoax—a failure of intelligence, judgment and character by many reporters and editors. The failure has continued in matters related to Hunter&#39;s laptop and Biden family influence-peddling.</p><p> How different would our world be if the American people had been able to rely on their national press for dispassionate, skeptical and honest reporting and analysis of both Mr. Trump and his enemies?</p><p> If, in holding Mr. Trump accountable for his election lies, it had also been seen holding his enemies accountable for their lies?</p><p> Every incentive at every point would have been different, for the FBI, for Adam Schiff, for Mr. Trump himself, for voters.特朗普和拜登今天会成为候选人吗？ Think it through and the answer is probably not. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Business World</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-is-hollywoods-fake-villain-unions-strike-actors-writers-ai-jobs-studios-9cdb3ab4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">AI Is Hollywood&#39;s Fake Villain</a> <span class="date">August 1, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-is-a-geopolitical-disaster-biden-plea-deal-russia-twitter-4f2653e6?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Hunter Biden Is a Geopolitical Disaster</a> <span class="date">July 28, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/only-biden-can-elect-trump-hunter-joe-irs-justice-2024-investigation-2f02c2cb?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Only Biden Can Elect Trump in 2024</a> <span class="date">July 25, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> A properly functioning press facilitates accountability through politics and shared truths.它减轻了通过起诉追究责任的需求。现在，本来就有嫌疑的特朗普和亨特·拜登的起诉将成为 2024 年的焦点。本来就有嫌疑的穆勒调查将被召回，主要是因为两年来隐瞒了美国政府从未拥有共谋证据的事实。 For systematic if bureaucratic truth telling, we had to rely on Inspector General Michael Horowitz and special counsel John Durham</p> because, let&#39;s face it, the press preferred a coverup. It still does.<p></p><p> Mr. Trump <a href="https://www.newsweek.com/donald-trump-real-victim-russiagate-hoax-wasnt-me-it-was-american-people-opinion-1816466" target="_blank" class="icon none">writes</a> in Newsweek linking his current prosecution to the collusion farrago and Mr. Durham&#39;s findings. The 2024 election might as well be billed DOJ vs. DOJ.</p><p> The latest indictment strikes me as more of the same and disappointingly weak.它承认，特朗普在 2020 年大选问题上撒谎是受保护的言论。反复强调的犯罪是“共谋”，但共谋是指与他人同意并计划实施其他犯罪的犯罪。特别检察官杰克·史密斯将这一罪行称为欺诈，其中包括特朗普呼吁公职人员和法院对其虚假指控采取行动，但在没有证据的情况下，没有人采取行动。这个过程奏效了。我们所有的流程都假设某些声明是错误的，甚至是恶意提出的。 A scintilla of evidence that Mr. Trump intended or planned the Jan. 6 riot would have been the case to bring, but Mr. Smith apparently found none.</p><p> Mr. Smith&#39;s indictment does deliver Mr. Biden a Jan. 6 talking point but no indictment was needed for that. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=526AA661-97D0-46C2-9AB6-B4C8E9331062&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fits-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Review and Outlook: Special counsel Jack Smith&#39;s latest indictment is based on a broad and novel theory of fraud against the US and serves the Democratic goal of making the 2024 election a referendum on Jan. 6, 2021. Images: Jane Rosenberg/Reuters/AP Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee<category> justice department</category><category> influence peddling</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>trump</category><category>起诉书</category><category>email server</category><category> comey</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Chris Christie, on the Record]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Excerpts from the Journal&#39;s Aug. 1 editorial board meeting with the former New Jersey governor and GOP presidential candidate. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590129954026207796"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11221797970291203701404590129954026207796"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 5:37 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chris-christie-on-the-record-election-gop-president-trump-desantis-climate-policy-crime-schools-419ea668"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830060?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Republican presidential candidate and former New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie in Kyiv, Ukraine, Aug. 4.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Efrem Lukatsky/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <strong>On why he&#39;s running for president:</strong></p><p> To me, at this point, our country feels a lot like the late &#39;70s: a country that&#39;s pretty horribly divided, angry, a country where inflation is running rampant, people feel insecure about the economy. You know, back in the &#39;70s, foreign-policy issues were difficult: hostages in Iran, Soviets in Afghanistan, Olympic boycott, and a president who basically appeared to be either unwilling or unable—or a combination of both—to be able to handle the depth of the problems and to have ideas that a majority of American people are willing to accept to try to solve them.</p><p> And what the country did in 1980 was take a conservative governor from a blue state who knew how to get things done.我认为情况是，我们现在在华盛顿所处的阶段并不是人们不想完成任何事情。他们甚至不知道如何把事情做好。现任总统没有足够的智力、体力或情感能量来做到这一点——即使他在职业生涯中曾经一度知道如何做到这一点，我认为他做到了。没有人花时间或有经验来知道如何解决这些问题。</p><p> And I think that&#39;s one of the things that discourages the American people as much as they are discouraged.因为即使他们相信某个人——就像许多人相信特朗普不得不说的一些事情一样——他去了那里，也没有表现出完成这些事情的能力。 Whether it was dealing with the budget, dealing with the border, dealing with healthcare—all things that he said and made big pronouncements on but showed that he had no ability, even with a Republican Congress, to be able to get anything done pretty much other than a tax cut, which was fine by me and I would support its renewal.</p><p> But I think the case is you need somebody who is tough enough to have the fights that need to be had but experienced enough and smart enough to know when to make a deal and to get things done and put some touchdowns in the end zone. 。 。 。 Governing in a blue state for eight years with a Democratic legislature . 。 。 we got things done on pensions and health benefits and crime and criminal-justice reform and got things done on educational choice that people thought would be impossible in a state like New Jersey to do, but we got a lot of it done. We didn&#39;t get everything we wanted, but we got a lot more than anybody thought we would.</p><p> Lastly, Trump can&#39;t win. 。 。 。 By the time we get to the debate stage in three weeks, he will probably be out on bail in four different jurisdictions. I hardly think that&#39;s going to play well. 。 。 。</p><p> How anybody in the Republican Party thinks that that&#39;s going to be appealing to the independent voters, the suburban women that we lost in 2020, which cost us the election, that we&#39;re going to get them back because, well, we&#39;re nominating a candidate who&#39;s on indictment in four jurisdictions, not to mention all the other problems. That&#39;s why I&#39;m not taking the polls at this moment too seriously. And no one else is willing to take him on. 。 。 。 They all are either playing for a position in a potential Trump cabinet or they just don&#39;t have the ability to do it.</p><p> <strong>On what he learned from 2016:</strong></p><p> There&#39;s no way to beat this guy unless you beat him. And the idea that we tried out in 2016—I was there and I participated in it, wrongfully—which was to allow him just to do what he was going to do and assuming no one&#39;s going to take him seriously . 。 。 was a failure for me, for Jeb Bush, for Scott Walker, for Marco Rubio, for Rand Paul and Ted Cruz, and all the rest of us and John Kasich.</p> We all tried it, it all failed, and it will fail this time. And I think Gov. DeSantis is leading the pack now and showing how much that strategy, when you combine it with a winning personality, fails.<p></p><p> <strong>On the first two indictments against Mr. Trump:</strong></p><p> New York is a joke. It shouldn&#39;t have been done as a matter of law. It shouldn&#39;t have been done as a matter of prosecutorial discretion. Let&#39;s do it as a matter of law first. They are stretching those statutes to their absolute limit and I think beyond them to charge him in the way that they did, to get felonies, which is what they wanted to get. So I think it&#39;s a matter of law, there&#39;s going to be a real question about whether or not those charges hold up in front of a judge.</p><p> But as a matter of prosecutorial discretion, it is obscene. 。 。 。 I think a payment to a porn star seven years ago, if that wrong is righted, will not improve the quality of life in the island of Manhattan one scintilla. And that&#39;s your first job as a prosecutor, to protect the rights and safety of the people in your jurisdiction. This is purely a political prosecution by Alvin Bragg. He ran on it and said he would do it. He&#39;s doing it. He&#39;s playing to a constituency here in New York that in Manhattan, it&#39;s not a big <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a></p> constituency, and I think that&#39;s the only way to explain it.<p></p><p> Now the underlying conduct is reprehensible. And I think you have to separate the two. I don&#39;t think he should have been charged politically, but paying off a woman that you had an affair with months before a presidential election in order to buy her silence so the American people don&#39;t know that this is part of your character plate is reprehensible conduct. For people in the country who are voting, they should know about it, but it didn&#39;t need to be charged.</p><p> The classified documents case I think is a serious case, with serious evidence, with—if as alleged in the indictment—absolute violations of the law. And so, from a legal perspective, I don&#39;t see any problem with it at all. From a prosecutorial-discretion perspective, I don&#39;t buy the argument that the way we right the wrong that was committed by Loretta Lynch and Jim Comey is to then let the next guy off, if he happens to be of the other party. 。 。 。 These are real crimes and the obstruction and now the superseding indictment is an example of his disregard for the law. 。 。 。</p><p> So I think the case against Trump on the classified documents is serious. If the conduct as alleged is proven beyond a reasonable doubt, there&#39;s no question it&#39;s a crime, both on the classified documents and on the obstruction. And if he takes the case to trial and loses, there&#39;s a presumption of jail for him.</p><p> The one other thing I would say about the case is that I wouldn&#39;t have charged it that way. I wouldn&#39;t have charged the classified documents portion of it, and not because those crimes aren&#39;t serious crimes—they are. But if your goal is to interfere as little as possible in the election, charge the case as narrowly as you possibly can so that the case will get to trial as quickly as possible and be resolved before people have to vote. When you add the classified documents into it, you&#39;re adding an element that will delay the trial. It&#39;s already delayed until May of next year and my guess is it won&#39;t happen then either. 。 。 。 You could just charge this as a straight obstruction and false statements to federal agents. 。 。 。</p><p> They quietly, professionally, privately asked him for 18 months to return the documents. He didn&#39;t, of course, because he was too busy. Now, I watched what he was doing for those 18 months—it seemed like mostly playing golf every day and giving interviews to people who were writing books about him. I think he could have squeezed a couple of minutes in to maybe go through the boxes and return documents that were classified. 。 。 。</p><p> How about we not try to predict the political dynamic and just do what&#39;s right? And then, let the chips fall where they may. And if it turns out that indicting Donald Trump re-elects him president, while that would trouble me deeply, what would trouble me more is if we let him get away with significant crimes against the country and said because it might help elect him, we&#39;re going to let him get away with it. Because that&#39;s what he&#39;s counting on. And beside his massive ego, it&#39;s the only other reason he&#39;s running. You think he gives a crap about the country and he&#39;s got all these great plans for the future of the country? Have you heard any of them? Every one of these speeches is about what happened three years ago. He&#39;s doesn&#39;t have a great plan for the country. But he&#39;s smart enough . 。 。 to know that if he&#39;s a candidate, there are going to be people out there who say, “I got to vote for him because he&#39;s being picked on or we&#39;re going to criticize the justice system for this because of it.”</p><p> <strong>On the Hunter Biden case and whether it reflects a double standard:</strong></p><p> For three weeks—go back and look at the tapes—I was saying the judge is not going to accept this plea because it&#39;s a one-sided plea, and she&#39;s going to look at it and say: What&#39;s the government get here? 。 。 。</p><p> The fact is that if it was corruption, the system stopped it. The judge did her job. 。 。 。 Most of [the federal judges] that I know and I interacted with are not impacted by politics and don&#39;t care about politics, because guess what? They got lifetime tenure. 。 。 。</p><p> I never met David Weiss, but if I was the US attorney and one of my prosecutors brought me that plea on any case, let alone a case that I knew was going to get worldwide scrutiny, the first thing I would have done, was fire them and then assign two new AUSAs [assistant US attorneys] who could actually bring me a competent plea back. David Weiss obviously didn&#39;t do that. So David Weiss is either lying that he had the jurisdiction he says he had to make the decision on his own, and he was getting pressure from above. Or he is incompetent and thought that was going to be a plea that was going to be acceptable. 。 。 。</p><p> So my point in all this is that, you want <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> prosecuted? As soon as I see the evidence I&#39;m happy to have there be an impeachment inquiry, right? My view is that Hunter Biden should have had to eat felony tax pleas given the amount of money that was involved and should have had to eat the gun charge. And if he&#39;s unwilling to do that, then you bring the trial because the trial&#39;s a lay-up, man. This is not a multiple LLC tax scheme. This is: this much came in, here are the 1099s, this is what you paid, there&#39;s the delta. 。 。 。</p><p> I think they should appoint a special counsel because I don&#39;t think Merrick Garland can be trusted anymore to do this. And you&#39;re really going to let David Weiss take a second crack at this? I mean, it&#39;s ridiculous. There should be a special counsel who should have brought enough jurisdiction to also look at the allegations that are now being made about the president&#39;s involvement with his son&#39;s business.</p><p> <strong>On his own relationship with Mr. Trump:</strong></p><p> I&#39;m not a Never Trumper, as you know, who never tried to help him, never supported him, was against him the whole time. I&#39;m actually coming from the perspective of, I tried to make this guy a better candidate, I tried to make him a better president. I did almost everything I could to do that. He disappointed me and he disappointed the country. I think you have more credibility when you&#39;re making the argument to Republican voters from that perspective, then if you&#39;re someone who has never been supportive of the president.</p><p> <strong>On what&#39;s changed in the Republican Party:</strong></p><p> I think you have voters who are now voting in the Republican primary who never voted before. 。 。 。 From the Republican Party, I think a lot of these middle-class voters, working-class voters, came to the conclusion that we cared more about world trade and what was happening in other countries than we cared about what&#39;s happening here economically. They became very disaffected with the Republican Party in that regard, even though they agree with us on a lot of other issues. But they hated Nafta, they hated the things that they felt were making them, their families, less marketable, less competitive, less employable.</p><p> The Democrats moved way far to the left. And so, these voters didn&#39;t see the Democrats, even though they liked some of their economic theories, but they moved so far culturally away from them, that they were no longer a viable alternative.</p><p> Enter Donald Trump . 。 。 somebody who is shameless in his willingness to say anything and talented in his ability to communicate it. And the combination of the two appeals to this group of folks. And they see him as somebody they&#39;d like to be. He&#39;s rich, he&#39;s famous, he&#39;s got a beautiful wife.</p><p> When you listen to some voters, and this is hardly all of them, but you listen to some—the idea of the profile that a three-times married, three-times bankrupt, billionaire, allegedly, real estate developer who lives in Manhattan would become the champion of people in central Pennsylvania—it is preposterous. But for this set of circumstances: the cultural departure by the Democrats to a place where these folks could not relate to them on a cultural basis at all, their view that Republican policy had abandoned them economically, and then a guy who comes in who they kind of would like to be like, and seems like the kind of guy who will say and do anything, and that&#39;s kind of appealing to them because they feel like nothing else is breaking through.</p><p> <strong>On Ron DeSantis:</strong></p><p> I mean, if we were endorsing résumés, then the DeSantis campaign would be neck and neck with Trump, if not ahead. We don&#39;t. You actually have to go out and be a person, be a human being, and show that you can relate to other humans whose votes you want to have. And—I&#39;m sorry, you know, it&#39;s just the truth and you know it, and you&#39;ve seen it, and I&#39;m sorry that I have to be the one to say it, but it is what it is. You can&#39;t look at what&#39;s happening here and not say to yourself, jeez, why would this be happening?</p><p> Well people look at someone and they make judgments based upon how they interact with them. And whether it&#39;s the hill you want to die on is the curriculum on African-American studies in the K-12 school districts in Florida? OK. You want to send out homoerotic videos and then pretend they&#39;re not yours, but then get caught that they are yours? I mean, this is like amateur hour and people see that, and they go, oh, maybe he&#39;s not ready to be president. Despite the fact that he did this, this, this in a red state with a red legislature and no discernible critical media in the entire state. OK, I wish I would have had those benefits when I was governor. You would have been, you know, giving me a parade in the Canyon of Heroes. I mean, come on.</p><p> <strong>On the Aug. 23 first Republican primary debate:</strong></p><p> There is only one person right now who matters in this primary, and it&#39;s Donald Trump. That&#39;s it. I don&#39;t waste my time predominately on other people. Now, if someone says something monumentally stupid, and I see it as the moment to say, “That&#39;s really stupid,” I&#39;m going to do it. 。 。 。 Yes, I have a plan, but I am absolutely both willing and able to change the plan on the fly, depending upon what happens on the stage.</p><p> <strong>On what happens if Mr. Trump doesn&#39;t show up to the debate:</strong></p><p> Doesn&#39;t matter. Doesn&#39;t matter to me, won&#39;t change what I&#39;m going to do. He&#39;s still the central focus and issue, except I&#39;ll have more time. And he won&#39;t respond. He&#39;ll be sitting in Bedminster on Truth Social going berserk. That&#39;s why I don&#39;t think—if he skips it, I don&#39;t think it will last long.</p><p> <strong>On the Christie policy agenda:</strong></p><p> First is that we&#39;ve got to go back to controlling government spending. It&#39;s what caused the inflation that we&#39;re still living with. And the fact is that I dealt with this when I was governor. 。 。 。 I inherited $11 billion deficit on the $29 billion budget and everybody said that I was going to have to raise taxes to balance it. I didn&#39;t, we didn&#39;t raise taxes for eight years. And that first year, we cut 836 individual programs out of the budget along with other measures to get ourselves into balance. We&#39;re not going to balance this budget in four years, and probably not going to balance it at all, in the first term, given the level of the debt and deficits that we have. But you got to start moving in that direction and showing people that you could do that.</p><p> Second, the K-12 educational system in this country is failing every family in this country. And by that, I don&#39;t mean that no one&#39;s getting a good education, but the ones who are, are paying much too much in taxes for what they&#39;re getting. And the ones that aren&#39;t are also paying those taxes and not getting a good education. And I think we need a completely new approach to the K-12 educational system. And I think that even the system that we have now in some states of vouchers for people only in a certain economic class is no longer what fixes the problem. I think we need to make that universal in the country, that everyone should be able to choose where they send their kids to school. 。 。 。 I am tired of having the teachers unions in this country decide exactly how this is going to go. 。 。 。</p><p> On crime, I am tired of seeing what&#39;s happening in New York, Chicago, Los Angeles, San Francisco and all these places. And I&#39;m going to go to each one of these states and appoint US attorneys, and their policy instruction from me is to go after violent crime in each one of these cities, to supersede the local authorities on it, to take these folks federal and to put them in jail. And when the localities get tired of it, of us intervening, then they&#39;re going to go back to doing it themselves. But until they&#39;re willing to do it themselves, we&#39;re going to do it. 。 。 。</p><p> In terms of our posture around the world, I am an unabashed supporter of Ukraine. I absolutely believe this is a proxy war by China against us. They are funding the Russian war effort; they are coordinating the provision of more sophisticated weapons to Russia with Iran. And we need to fight this fight there and now because otherwise we&#39;ll be fighting it with American troops someplace else in the world at China&#39;s instigation, directly or even indirectly.</p><p> And I don&#39;t believe that we&#39;re a country that can&#39;t do all those things at the same time. You know, this idea that somehow an America First agenda is an agenda which must turn its back on the rest of the world is contrary, in my view, to our historical experience. 。 。 。 I would give [Ukraine] F-16s. I would have done it a long time ago. I would have been much more aggressive even than the Trump administration was in terms of providing them with offensive weapons in addition to defensive weapons, that they needed to, at that time, deter the war. 。 。 。</p><p> We need to make it very clear to the Chinese that they can continue to play and say that there is no limit to the friendship between Russia and China. There may be no limit, but there will be a cost.</p><p> <strong>On federal involvement with funding schools:</strong></p><p> Well, I think you start with leveraging, the $80-plus billion or so that the feds do spend on K-12 education and say to them, the only way that money is going to your jurisdiction is if it goes into accounts for these families and leverage that money that way. 。 。 。 Because in a lot of these states, you already have close to this system, and so you need to go and make the argument for this. This is a moral argument. These folks—families are getting ripped off by this educational system, both in terms of dollars and in hope. And you got to go out and make the case, you got to use the presidential bully pulpit to do it. It is not going to be easy, but I refuse to continue to invest in a system that&#39;s producing failure at every level. 。 。 。</p><p> When you look at the NAEP scores that came out in the last three months, it is now a trend that reading and math scores continue to go down. And yes, some of it is Covid-blamed, but part of the reason that that happened was because the teachers unions were deciding policy during Covid and not the public officials in many states.</p><p> <strong>On the tax code:</strong></p><p> I would renew the Trump tax cuts. I think that they were the right prescription at the time and I think they produced results. 。 。 。 The more we can get the government towards a flatter tax, is what we should be doing. I don&#39;t think we&#39;ll ever have a flat federal tax, but moving it much more towards that.</p><p> <strong>On energy and climate policy:</strong></p><p> I think that we have gone much too far. We are way out ahead of not only the American people, but we&#39;re way out ahead of the technology and the availability of it. And not only, using EV as an example, not only the technology of EVs but the technology of actually fueling EVs. 。 。 。</p><p> One of the things that I would really push for is increase in nuclear. And that comes from my experience in New Jersey, we&#39;re the most densely populated state in the country by far. Fifty-three percent of our electricity is from nuclear. If you can safely run nuclear in the most densely populated state in the country, which we have for now four decades, you can certainly do it in every other area of the country. 。 。 。</p><p> This has to be a bigger conversation with China. We&#39;ve lowered our CO2 emissions by a billion tons a year over the last decade. At the same time, China has increased them by five billion tons a year over the last decade. I believe in climate change, but we&#39;re not going to solve it by ourselves and our Western European friends.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chris-christie-on-the-record-election-gop-president-trump-desantis-climate-policy-crime-schools-419ea668</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chris-christie-on-the-record-election-gop-president-trump-desantis-climate-policy-crime-schools-419ea668<category>选举</category><category>总统</category><category>2024年</category><category>new jersey</category><category> interview</category><category>犯罪</category><category>学校</category><category>tax code</category><category> gop</category><category> climate policy</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>社论</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Warren and Graham Emulate History’s Failed Regulators]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The ICC and FCC stifled innovation in railroads and radio, respectively. Why do the same to Big Tech with a Digital Consumer Protection Commission? <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126492172953272"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590126492172953272"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Richard N. Langlois</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 2:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/warren-and-graham-emulate-historys-failed-regulators-innovation-big-tech-firms-1ca2002d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829582?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Union Pacific Railroad train in Joliet, Ill., Sept. 13, 2022.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: tannen maury/EPA/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> To the envy of the world, American companies dominate technology, especially the Big Five: Alphabet, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">Apple</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="">Microsoft</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span> Since the federal government played some role in the development of the underlying technologies—semiconductors, computers, software and the internet—these world-beating high-tech firms might be counted as a success of US “industrial policy.”</p><p> So why has a bipartisan movement risen to hobble the American national champions? Senators Lindsey Graham (R., SC) and Elizabeth Warren (D., Mass.) have proposed a Digital Consumer Protection Commission to license and regulate high-tech firms. Their model is such independent bodies as the Interstate Commerce Commission and the Federal Communications Commission.</p><p> Mr. Graham and Ms. Warren assure us that their new commission would “preserve innovation while minimizing harm presented by emerging industries,” but a careful look at history suggests otherwise. The ICC, the FCC and other agencies frequently hindered innovation, sometimes drastically. They were generally politicized and opaque. And they often worked against the long-term interests of consumers.</p><p> Railroads were the first great irruption of American industrial policy, as (usually corrupt) land grants and subsidies fueled overbuilding and the misallocation of resources. By the late 19th century, the railroads had come to play a role like the one high-tech companies play today: They lowered transportation and transaction costs, dramatically altering the country&#39;s economic geography and opening up a vast array of economic possibilities.</p><p> The railroads harmed small merchants who were tied to the older system of roads and canals. But even those who benefited from railroads—notably farmers and producers of raw materials—feared the power of the enterprises that provided them with large new markets. The anxieties of innumerable small players generated powerful political energy, culminating in the Interstate Commerce Act of 1887, which created the ICC—and with it the template of the independent regulatory commission.</p><p> The historian Gabriel Kolko famously argued that the ICC was created by and for the railroads themselves, as a solution to a problem of intense competition. But more-recent research has shown that the interests of shippers were also at play, and by the early 20th century the ICC had essentially been captured by the shippers. The result for the railroads was absurdly low rates of return and an inability to raise capital. The ICC also became a bottleneck through which virtually all railroad business decisions had to pass.</p><p> Thus began the long and steady decline of the American railroad industry, which wasn&#39;t arrested until surface freight was deregulated (and the ICC ultimately abolished) in the 1970s. Throughout its life, the ICC repeatedly stood in the way of innovation, including containerized shipping.</p><p> Radio, the high-tech industry of the 1920s, offers similar lessons. Broadcasting calls for regulation, since stations can interfere with one another if they transmit on nearby frequencies at the same time and place. But this can be dealt with by creating property rights in electromagnetic spectrum, something toward which the common law was already groping. (Such a system would eventually be put in place during the Clinton administration.) Instead, Congress created the Federal Radio Commission, which became the FCC when television arrived.</p><p> Spectrum allocation immediately became intensely politicized. The fastest route to a station license required a detour through Capitol Hill. Like the ICC, the FCC became an information bottleneck, and this favored the well-capitalized major networks. The FCC also held back innovation, including famously delaying the advent of cellular telephony for decades by refusing to grant it spectrum.</p><p> Even for radio, where spectrum was abundant, the FCC made content a central criterion for receiving a license. This meant wholesome, mainstream, nondissident fare. The commission demanded that all stations give equal time to alternative viewpoints, effectively a tax on speech. Many on both sides of the political spectrum today look back with nostalgia on the days when everyone heard exactly the same news in the comforting voice of Walter Cronkite. But they forget the severe limitations that heavy-handed commission regulation placed on the volume of content—and the way it silenced dissenting voices of all kinds.</p><p> The problems of regulation weren&#39;t limited to the ICC and the FCC. They were structural problems of independent commissions. Mr. Graham and Ms. Warren complain that the leaders of the big-tech firms weren&#39;t elected by voters. But they were elected by millions of consumers and shareholders voting with their dollars. Regulatory commissions are elected neither by voters nor by consumers, and they have shown themselves opaque even to Congress, whose oversight committees inevitably came to share the views and values of the regulated industries.</p><p> It is fashionable nowadays to dismiss the Great Deregulation of the late 20th century as an unfortunate if fleeting episode of “neoliberalism.” In fact, dismantling some of America&#39;s rigid and retrogressive regulatory institutions unleashed powerful forces of innovation and consumer benefit. Before we attempt to rebuild those structures, we need to examine the lessons of history.</p><p> <em>Mr. Langlois is an economics professor at the University of Connecticut and author of “The Corporation and the Twentieth Century: The History of American Business Enterprise.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=308CC4D2-8328-495D-966C-0055C8060126&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwarren-and-graham-emulate-historys-failed-regulators-innovation-big-tech-firms-1ca2002d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、阿莉西亚·芬利 (Alysia Finley) 和金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片：盖蒂图片社/罗阿诺克时报，美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 18:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/warren-and-graham-emulate-historys-failed-regulators-innovation-big-tech-firms-1ca2002d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/warren-and-graham-emulate-historys-failed-regulators-innovation-big-tech-firms-1ca2002d<category> big tech</category><category> high tech firms</category><category>公司</category><category>规定</category><category>收音机</category><category>railroad</category><category> bipartisan</category><category> innovation</category><category> industrial policy</category><category> Rail Transport</category><category> Land Transport</category><category>技术</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Research/Development</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>林赛·格雷厄姆</category><category>政府政策</category><category>research</category><category> development</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category><category>rail transport</category><category> land transport</category><category>技术</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[H-2A Guest Workers Can Pick Florida’s Crops]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Farmers complain about the state&#39;s illegal-immigration law, but there is an alternative. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590082423995831204"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12705823021609713873204590082423995831204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Dave Seminara</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 2:12 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/h-2a-guest-workers-can-pick-floridas-crops-agriculture-farmer-immigration-desantis-363fdf22"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819968?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A woman works on a farm in Homestead, Fla., May 23.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: cristobal herrera-ulashkevich/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <em>St. Petersburg, Fla.</em></p><p> Who will harvest the crops? This powerful refrain comes up anytime conservatives propose or enact tough measures to combat illegal immigration. Florida&#39;s new law, SB 1718, which went into effect July 1, is a case in point. The law invalidates out-of-state driver&#39;s licenses given to illegal immigrants, requires hospitals to quantify uncompensated care given to them, and compels employers with at least 25 employees to use E-Verify to check the legal status of new hires, among other measures. A previous bill mandating the use of E-Verify, SB 664, exempted agriculture employers. But this one doesn&#39;t, and some Florida farmers are furious.</p><p> A grower in Homestead, near Miami, complained to a Telemundo reporter, “Who&#39;s going to harvest?” The owner of a produce-packaging facility in South Florida kvetched to a Journal reporter, “How are we going to run the farms?” Even Republican state Rep. Rick Roth, who voted for the bill, said he&#39;s upset that fearful farmworkers without legal status are leaving the state because of the bill.</p><p> “I&#39;m a farmer, and the farmers are mad as hell,” Mr. Roth said. “We are losing employees. They&#39;re already starting to move to Georgia and other states.”</p><p> Employers in other sectors are also unhappy with the new law. But Democrats, and some Republicans, have long used farmers&#39; staffing needs to argue against E-Verify and other tools to combat unlawful migration. Even George W. Bush invoked the plight of farmers to make this point in 2018. “Americans don&#39;t want to pick cotton at 105 degrees, but there are people who want to put food on their family&#39;s tables and are willing to do that,” he said at a 2018 summit in Abu Dhabi.</p><p> Thanks to inflation and soaring grocery bills, the prospect of food shortages and price increases is real. But farmers and their allies in the media seldom acknowledge that they have a powerful employment tool in the H-2A visa to import guest workers. Unlike the H-1B visa for skilled labor and the H-2B for unskilled labor, the H-2A is uncapped. Farmers can theoretically bring in all the labor they need, as long as they can prove they can&#39;t find local workers.</p><p> The media largely ignores the H-2A visa because it contradicts the preferred narrative about unlawful immigration. The same is true of the TN visa, another fast-growing, numerically unlimited guest-worker program for Mexican and Canadians in dozens of skilled professions. But more employers are discovering these programs. A decade ago, the State Department approved 77,010 H-2A visas. In fiscal 2022, the figure climbed to 298,000. This year, employers are on pace to shatter that record. In the first five months of the year, the State Department approved 163,792 H-2A farmworkers from Mexico alone.</p><p> The program figures to grow in popularity as more red states crack down on illegal immigration. H-2A workers are less likely to quit than illegal immigrants or local hires because their legal status is tied to their employment, and they are authorized to work only for the petitioning employer for up to three years at a time. Farmers like that.</p><p> What they don&#39;t like is the program&#39;s complexity. The requirements are bewildering for most farmers, who typically hire immigration attorneys to navigate the red tape. Farmers must demonstrate that they tried to recruit workers locally—though unappealing, pro forma job ads usually work. They also must not have laid off American workers within 60 days before petitioning. The Labor Department requires farmers to meet prevailing-wage requirements and provide free housing and meals or cooking facilities to H-2A recipients. Employers also must submit to annual preoccupancy inspections of worker housing to get the labor certification they need to secure guest workers.</p><p> Some farmers would rather pay illegal workers in cash and risk an Immigration and Customs Enforcement raid than invite government scrutiny of their operations. The threat of ICE raids has receded significantly under the Biden administration, so it&#39;s easy to see why SB 1718 is unpopular with Florida growers. Still, their complaints seem overblown. The law applies only to new hires and not existing employees—a fact that most media outlets haven&#39;t made clear, causing unnecessary panic among migrant farmworkers.</p><p> Florida&#39;s new law doesn&#39;t apply to employers with fewer than 25 employees. Last year the Labor Department changed H-2A rules allowing groups of small farmers to file a single petition and share the costs of importing guest workers.</p><p> Those outraged by Florida&#39;s new law should instead champion programs like the H-2A visa. Legal workers in a program with plenty of labor-protection standards are far less likely to be exploited than workers with no legal status. It remains to be seen how the law will affect Florida farmers, but many who&#39;ve become addicted to illegal labor could soon start hiring legally. That would be a nice change.</p><p> <em>Mr. Seminara is a former diplomat and host of the “DeSantisland” podcast.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
